--- title: "SBD clustering" author: "Raphael Saldanha" date: last-modified bibliography: references.bib --- This notebooks aims to reproduce the metodology of the paper submitted to the SBD2023 conference, implementing the global and subset modelling. This methodology aims to compare the perfomance of models trained with data from all municipalities time-series (*global models*) and models trained with subset of munipalities time-series (*subset models*). Those subset will be created by a clustering algorithm considering the municipalities cases time-series. ## Packages ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} library(tidyverse) library(arrow) library(tidymodels) library(bonsai) library(finetune) library(modeltime) library(timetk) library(dtwclust) library(kableExtra) library(tictoc) library(geobr) library(DT) ``` ::: ## Load data ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tdengue <- read_parquet(file = "../tdengue.parquet") %>% drop_na() %>% select(mun, date, starts_with("cases")) ``` ::: ::: callout-note - NA values are created when the lagged variables were calculated. The rows containing those NA values are dropped due machine learning regressors constraints. - For validation purposes, only the `cases` and `cases_lag*` covariates variables are keep. ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} glimpse(tdengue) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` Rows: 161,370 Columns: 9 $ mun "110002", "110002", "110002", "110002", "110002", "110002",… $ date 2011-02-06, 2011-02-13, 2011-02-20, 2011-02-27, 2011-03-06… $ cases -0.51044592, 0.07880156, 0.66804904, 0.07880156, -0.5104459… $ cases_lag1 2.43579149, -0.51044592, 0.07880156, 0.66804904, 0.07880156… $ cases_lag2 0.66804904, 2.43579149, -0.51044592, 0.07880156, 0.66804904… $ cases_lag3 0.07880156, 0.66804904, 2.43579149, -0.51044592, 0.07880156… $ cases_lag4 0.66804904, 0.07880156, 0.66804904, 2.43579149, -0.51044592… $ cases_lag5 0.66804904, 0.66804904, 0.07880156, 0.66804904, 2.43579149,… $ cases_lag6 -0.51044592, 0.66804904, 0.66804904, 0.07880156, 0.66804904… ``` ::: ::: ## Clustering This procedure goal is to cluster the municipalities considering the cases time series similarities between them. ### Prepare data Prepare the data for use with the `dtwclust` package, pivoting the panel data to a wide format and matrix object. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} cdengue <- tdengue %>% select(mun, date, cases) %>% mutate(mun = paste0("m_", mun)) %>% arrange(mun, date) %>% pivot_wider(names_from = mun, values_from = cases) %>% select(-date) %>% t() %>% tslist() ``` ::: ### SBD method The SBD method is used to cluster the municipalities, considering a shape-bases distance (k-Shape clustering algorithm) [@paparrizos2015]. 326 municipalities will be clustered. The clustering algorithm is applied with a varying number of $k$ partitions from 3 to 8. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} k_seq <- 3:8 tic() clust <- tsclust( series = cdengue, type = "partitional", k = k_seq, distance = "sbd", seed = 123 ) toc() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` 0.257 sec elapsed ``` ::: ::: ### Cluster Validity Indices (CVI) To choose the number of partitions, the Silhouette statistic is observed. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} names(clust) <- paste0("k_", k_seq) res_cvi <- sapply(clust, cvi, type = "internal") %>% t() %>% as_tibble(rownames = "k") %>% arrange(-Sil) res_cvi %>% kbl() %>% kable_styling() ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} `````{=html}
k Sil SF CH DB DBstar D COP
k_3 0.1747336 0.3501838 36.98758 2.260992 2.400068 0.0805315 0.3705055
k_4 0.1669509 0.2526978 34.15648 4.050796 4.597881 0.0676247 0.3688632
k_7 0.1625835 0.1135484 20.46483 2.802248 3.289527 0.0805315 0.3497498
k_8 0.1294623 0.1012342 20.25096 1.906407 2.268955 0.0660755 0.3456895
k_6 0.0914225 0.1541329 29.42529 4.230747 7.206356 0.0280277 0.3317256
k_5 0.0517861 0.1915811 27.11958 3.855824 5.374118 0.0353306 0.3523987
````` ::: ::: ### Select cluster with higher Silhouette statistic ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} sel_clust <- clust[[res_cvi[[1,1]]]] plot(sel_clust) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](dengue_ts_global_subset_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-7-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: ### Cluster sizes ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} table(sel_clust@cluster) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` 1 2 3 34 251 41 ``` ::: ::: ### Identify municipalities and cluster id Finally, the cluster partition ID is added to the main dataset. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} cluster_ids <- tibble( mun = names(cdengue) %>% substr(3, 9), group = as.character(sel_clust@cluster) ) ``` ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tdengue <- left_join(tdengue, cluster_ids, by = "mun") ``` ::: ## Train and test split Split the data into training and testing. The function `time_series_split` handles the time series, not shuffling them, and considering the panel data format, as depicted in the message about overlapping timestamps detected. The last two years data will be used as the training set. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tdengue_split <- tdengue %>% time_series_split( date_var = date, assess = 52*2, cumulative = TRUE ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Data is not ordered by the 'date_var'. Resamples will be arranged by `date`. ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Overlapping Timestamps Detected. Processing overlapping time series together using sliding windows. ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} tdengue_split ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` <127466/33904/161370> ``` ::: ::: #### K-folds The training set will be split into k folds. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tdengue_split_folds <- training(tdengue_split) %>% vfold_cv(v = 5) ``` ::: ## Recipes The global and subset models training specification are called recipes. The procedure bellow creates a list of those recipes. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} recipes_list <- list() ``` ::: ### Global The global training recipe uses data from all municipalities for training the models. - The date and group variables are removed prior training - The municipality identification variable is treated as an Id variable, taking no place as a predictor in the training process ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} recipe_global <- recipe(cases ~ ., data = training(tdengue_split)) %>% step_rm(date, group) %>% update_role(mun, new_role = "id variable") recipes_list <- append(recipes_list, list(global = recipe_global)) rm(recipe_global) ``` ::: ### Groups - For each group created by the clustering process, a specific training recipe will be created. For this, the first step is to filter rows from the training set, keep only the rows belonging to the group in the loop - The date and group variables are removed prior training - The municipality identification variable is treated as an Id variable, taking no place as a predictor in the training process ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} for(g in unique(tdengue$group)){ tmp <- recipe(cases ~ ., data = training(tdengue_split)) %>% step_filter(group == !!g) %>% step_rm(date, group) %>% update_role(mun, new_role = "id variable") tmp <- list(tmp) tmp <- setNames(tmp, paste0("g", g)) recipes_list <- append(recipes_list, tmp) rm(tmp) } ``` ::: ## Regressors specification ### Random forest A Random Forest specification using the `ranger` engine. The `trees` and `min_n` hyperparameters will be tuned. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} rf_spec <- rand_forest( trees = tune(), min_n = tune() ) %>% set_engine("ranger") %>% set_mode("regression") ``` ::: ### LightGBM ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # lgbm_spec <- boost_tree( # trees = tune(), # min_n = tune(), # tree_depth = tune() # ) %>% # set_engine("lightgbm") %>% # set_mode("regression") ``` ::: ## Workflow set This step creates a workflow set, combining the training recipes and regressors specifications. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} all_workflows <- workflow_set( preproc = recipes_list, models = list(rf = rf_spec), cross = TRUE ) ``` ::: ## Tune This step tunes the training hyperparameters of each workflow. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} doParallel::registerDoParallel() tic() race_results <- all_workflows %>% workflow_map( "tune_race_anova", seed = 345, resamples = tdengue_split_folds, grid = 10, control = control_race(parallel_over = "everything"), verbose = TRUE ) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` i 1 of 4 tuning: global_rf ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Warning in mclapply(argsList, FUN, mc.preschedule = preschedule, mc.set.seed = set.seed, : scheduled core 5 did not deliver a result, all values of the job will be affected ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` ✔ 1 of 4 tuning: global_rf (25m 1.5s) ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` i 2 of 4 tuning: g3_rf ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` ✔ 2 of 4 tuning: g3_rf (2m 24s) ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` i 3 of 4 tuning: g1_rf ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` ✔ 3 of 4 tuning: g1_rf (1m 19.9s) ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` i 4 of 4 tuning: g2_rf ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` ✔ 4 of 4 tuning: g2_rf (18m 47.6s) ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} toc() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` 2853.792 sec elapsed ``` ::: ::: ## Fit Each workflow will be trained using the tuned hyperparameters, considering the RMSE metric as reference. This procedure creates a list of trained models, containing the fit results and a list of the municipalities used on the training of each workflow. The global workflow is trained with data from all municipalities and the subsets workflows are trained using the respective municipalities list given by the cluster algorithm. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} tic() trained_models <- list() for(w in unique(race_results$wflow_id)){ best_tune <- race_results %>% extract_workflow_set_result(w) %>% select_best("rmse") final_fit <- race_results %>% extract_workflow(w) %>% finalize_workflow(best_tune) %>% fit(training(tdengue_split)) mold <- extract_mold(final_fit) train_ids <- mold$extras$roles$`id variable` %>% distinct() %>% pull() %>% as.character() final_fit <- list( list( "final_fit" = final_fit, "train_ids" = train_ids ) ) final_fit <- setNames(final_fit, paste0(w)) trained_models <- append(trained_models, final_fit) } toc() ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` 369.351 sec elapsed ``` ::: ::: ## Accuracy After training each workflow, the accuracy of the models are obtained applying the fitted models on the testing set. For the global model, all municipalities are using for testing. For the subsets models, only data from the subset's municipalities are considered for testing. The RMSE metric is obtained for each workflow and municipality. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} models_accuracy <- tibble() for(t in 1:length(trained_models)){ model_tbl <- modeltime_table(trained_models[[t]][[1]]) testing_set <- testing(tdengue_split) %>% filter(mun %in% trained_models[[t]][[2]]) calib_tbl <- model_tbl %>% modeltime_calibrate( new_data = testing_set, id = "mun" ) res <- calib_tbl %>% modeltime_accuracy( acc_by_id = TRUE, metric_set = metric_set(rmse) ) res$.model_id <- word(names(trained_models[t]), 1, sep = "_") models_accuracy <- bind_rows(models_accuracy, res) } ``` ::: This plot presents the RMSE distribution across the workflows. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} ggplot(data = models_accuracy, aes(x = .model_id, y = rmse, fill = .model_desc)) + geom_boxplot() ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](dengue_ts_global_subset_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-22-1.png){width=672} ::: ::: ### Breakdown ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} mun_names <- lookup_muni(code_muni = "all") %>% mutate(code_muni = substr(code_muni, 0, 6)) %>% mutate(name_muni = paste0(name_muni, ", ", abbrev_state)) %>% select(code_muni, name_muni) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Using year 2010 ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} models_accuracy %>% left_join(mun_names, by = c("mun" = "code_muni")) %>% select(.model_id, .model_desc, name_muni, rmse) %>% mutate(rmse = round(rmse, 2)) %>% arrange(.model_id, .model_desc, -rmse) %>% datatable(filter = "top") ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} models_accuracy %>% left_join(mun_names, by = c("mun" = "code_muni")) %>% select(.model_id, .model_desc, name_muni, rmse) %>% mutate(rmse = round(rmse, 2)) %>% group_by(.model_desc) %>% mutate(.model_id = case_when( .model_id != "global" ~ "cluster", .default = .model_id )) %>% pivot_wider(names_from = .model_id, values_from = rmse) %>% mutate(dif = round(global - cluster, 2)) %>% ungroup() %>% datatable(filter = "top") ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} models_accuracy %>% left_join(mun_names, by = c("mun" = "code_muni")) %>% select(.model_id, .model_desc, name_muni, rmse) %>% group_by(.model_desc) %>% mutate(.model_id = case_when( .model_id != "global" ~ "cluster", .default = .model_id )) %>% pivot_wider(names_from = .model_id, values_from = rmse) %>% mutate(dif = round(global - cluster, 2)) %>% arrange(.model_desc, dif) %>% ggplot(aes(x = global, y = cluster, fill = .model_desc, color = dif)) + geom_point(size = 2, alpha = .3) + viridis::scale_color_viridis(option = "inferno") + theme_bw() + labs(x = "Global model", y = "Subset models", title = "RMSE error obtained with global and subset training strategies") ``` ::: {.cell-output-display}
